Given that the function $y=x+\frac{a}{x} (a>0)$ is monotonically decreasing in the interval $(0,\sqrt{a}]$ and monotonically increasing in the interval $[\sqrt{a},+\infty)$, and that the function $h(x)=(x^{2}+\frac{1}{x})^{3}+(x+\frac{1}{x^{2}})^{3} (x\in[\frac{1}{2},2])$
(1) Write out the monotonic intervals of the function $f(x)=x^{2}+\frac{a}{x^{2}} (a>0)$ and the function $g(x)=x^{n}+\frac{a}{x^{n}} (a>0,n\in N,n\geqslant 3)$ in $(0,+\infty)$ (only write the conclusion, do not prove);
(2) Find the maximum and minimum values of the function $h(x)$;
(3) Discuss the number of real roots of the equation $h^{2}(x)-3mh(x)+2m^{2}=0 (0 < m\leqslant 30)$.

solution:
(1) According to the conditions, the monotonically decreasing interval of $f(x)=x^{2}+\frac{a}{x^{2}} (a>0)$ is $(0,\sqrt[4]{a}]$, and the monotonically increasing interval is $[\sqrt[4]{a},+\infty)$;
The monotonically decreasing interval of the function $g(x)=x^{n}+\frac{a}{x^{n}}$ is $(0,\sqrt[2n]{a}]$, and the monotonically increasing interval is $[\sqrt[2n]{a},+\infty)$;

(2) $h(x)=(x^{2}+\frac{1}{x})^{3}+(x+\frac{1}{x^{2}})^{3}=(x^{6}+\frac{1}{x^{6}})+4(x^{3}+\frac{1}{x^{3}})+6$
From (1), we know that both $x^{6}+\frac{1}{x^{6}}$ and $4(x^{3}+\frac{1}{x^{3}})$ are monotonically decreasing in $[\frac{1}{2},1]$ and monotonically increasing in $[1,2]$,
So the function $h(x)$ is monotonically decreasing in $[\frac{1}{2},1]$ and monotonically increasing in $[1,2]$,
Thus, the minimum value of $h(x)$ is $h(1)=\boxed{16}$, and the maximum value of $h(x)$ is $h(\frac{1}{2})=h(2)=\boxed{\frac{6561}{64}}$;

(3) From $h^{2}(x)-3mh(x)+2m^{2}=0$, we can get $(h(x)-m)(h(x)-2m)=0$,
So we have $h(x)=m$ or $h(x)=2m$,
Moreover, the function $h(x)$ is monotonically decreasing in $[\frac{1}{2},1]$ and monotonically increasing in $[1,2]$,
And $h(1)=16, h(\frac{1}{2})=h(2)=\frac{6561}{64}$,
So when $0  2m > 16 \Rightarrow 8 < m < 16$, the equation has two real roots;
When $m=16$, $2m=32$, the equation has three real roots;
When $16 < m \leqslant 30, 2m \leqslant 60 < \frac{6561}{64}$, the equation has four real roots.

In summary,
$\boxed{\text{When } 0 < m < 8, \text{ the equation has no real roots}}$;
$\boxed{\text{When } m=8, \text{ the equation has one real root}}$;
$\boxed{\text{When } 8 < m < 16, \text{ the equation has two real roots}}$;
$\boxed{\text{When } m=16, \text{ the equation has three real roots}}$;
$\boxed{\text{When } 16 < m \leqslant 30, \text{ the equation has four real roots}}$.

